## 🐛 Bug Report

Hi, I found out I am losing headers after reading an XLSX file I created.
I am creating a file then updating it its new rows each time. the update would work if I conserve
the original workbook object I got when creating the file. The update will not work if I read the file using `xlsx.readFile` because, as I found out,  the header Columns on my sheet will be set to undefined ( I get an array of columns with keys and headers set to undefined).

I don't think this behavior is normal, unless I am missing something with xlsx file format.

Lib version: "^3.8.2"

## Steps To Reproduce

<!-- The exact steps required to reproduce the issue, ideally with a code example -->

```javascript
const wb = new ExcelJS.Workbook();
const ws = wb.addWorksheet('XYZ');
ws.Columns= [{header : "XXX", key:"XXX"}];
await wb.writeFile(filePath);

const newWb = new ExcelJS.Workbook();
await newWb.readFile(filePath)
const newWs = wb.getWorksheet('XYZ');
console.log(newWs.Columns); // here we will find that the keys are set to undefined and not the keys we set 
//any object you add to the sheet will be discarded as the keys are set to undefined so no object matches the columns
//this will not add anything
newWs.addRow({XXX:"test"});
//and this will write the file but updates nothing
await newWb.writeFile(filePath);
```

## The expected behaviour:

keeping the Columns from the xlsx File and consequently updating correctly
